ewtheorem{example}[theorem]{Example}  egin{document}  egin{center} { f CONGRUENCES RELATING REGULAR PARTITION FUNCTIONS, A GENERALIZED TAU FUNCTION AND PARTITION FUNCTION WEIGHTED COMPOSITION SUMS}\vskip 20pt { f S. Sriram}\ {\smallit Post Graduate and Research Department of Mathematics, National College, \ Affiliated to Bharathidasan University, Tiruchirapalli, Tamil Nadu, India}\ {	t sriram.priya02@yahoo.com}\ \vskip 20pt { f A. David Christopher ootnote{Corresponding author}}\ {\smallit Department of Mathematics, The American College, Madurai, Tamil Nadu, India.}\ {\smallit Post Graduate and Research Department of Mathematics, National College,\ Affiliated to Bharathidasan University, Tiruchirapalli, Tamil Nadu, India}\ {	t davidchristopher@americancollege.edu.in}\ \vskip 20pt \end{center} \vskip 20pt \centerline{\smallit Received: , Accepted: , Published: } \vskip 30pt \centerline{ f Abstract} 
oindent Let $n$ and $t$ be positive integers with $t\geq 2$. Let $R_t(n)$ be the number of $t$-regular partitions of $n$. A class of functions, denoted $	au_k(n)$, is defined as follows: \[ q\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)^k=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au_k(n)q^n, \] where $k$ is an integer. We express $	au_k(n)$ as a binomial coefficient weighted partition sum. Consequently, we obtain congruence identities that relate $	au_k(n)$, $R_t(n)$ and partition function weighted composition sums. \pagestyle{myheadings} \markright{\smalltt INTEGERS:19(2019)\hfill} 	hispagestyle{empty}  aselineskip=12.875pt \vskip 30pt \section{Introduction} Euler \cite{euler} considered the following product-to-sum representation:  egin{equation*} \prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\omega(n)q^n, \end{equation*} and found that  egin{equation}\label{PNT} \omega(n)= egin{cases} (-1)^{l}&	ext{ if }n= rac{3l^2\pm l}{2};\ 0&	ext{ otherwise.} \end{cases} \end{equation} This is the celebrated Euler's pentagonal number theorem. Ramanujan \cite{ramanujan} considered the following product-to-sum representation:  egin{equation*} q\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}{(1-q^m)^{24}}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au(n)q^n, \end{equation*} and made the following conjectures:  egin{enumerate} \item $	au(nm)=	au(n)	au(m)$ if $\gcd(m,n)=1$, \item for prime $p$ and integer $r\geq 1$: $	au(p^{r+1})=	au(p)	au(p^r)-p^{11}	au(p^{r-1}), $ \item for prime $p$: $|	au(p)|\leq 2p^{ rac{11}{2}}. $ \end{enumerate} The first two were established by Mordell \cite{mordell-1}. Delinge \cite{delinge} established the third. The function $	au(n)$ defined above is known as Ramanujan's tau function. The following common generalization of the aforementioned functions of Ramanujan and Euler is the object of study in this article.  egin{definition}\label{main-definition} Let $k
eq 0$ be an integer. We define an arithmetical function, denoted $	au_k(n)$, in the following way:  egin{equation} q\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)^k=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au_k(n)q^n. \end{equation} \end{definition} Newman \cite{newman} and Kostant \cite{kostant} were concerned with the polynomial representation of $	au_k(n)$. Serre \cite{serre} and Heim et al \cite{Bernard} examined the natural density of the set $\{k\in\mathbb{N}: 	au_k(n)
eq 0\}$ at several instances of $n$. The main objective of this paper is to explore various arithmetic properties of $	au_k(n)$. We will first use the logarithmic derivative method to determine some arithmetic properties of $	au_k(n)$ (at specific instances of $k$). This forms the core part of Section 2. In Section 3, $	au_k(n)$ is expressed as a binomial coefficient weighted partition sum. As a result, congruence relations involving $	au_k(n)$ and $t$-regular partition functions are obtained (at certain instances of $k$ and $t$). In Section 4, an expression for $$ \sum_{\substack{{n=a_1+a_2+\cdots a_k}\{a_{i}\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}}}}p(a_{1})p(a_{2})\cdots p(a_{k})	ext{ modulo }{l} $$ is obtained, where $l$ is an odd prime number, and $p(n)$ is the number of partitions of $n$. \section{ Divisibility Properties of $	au_k(n)$ using Logarithmic Differentiation} In this section, we will discuss several congruence properties of $	au_k(n)$ when the modulus belongs to the set $\{k-1\}\cup\{d\in\mathbb N:d|k\}$. \subsection{ $	au_k(n)$ Modulo $k-1$ when $k-1$ is a Prime Number}  egin{proposition}\label{modulok-1} Let $n$ be a positive integer, and let $k-1$ be a prime number. If $0\leq n-1- rac{3r^2\pm r}{2}
ot\equiv 0\pmod{(k-1)}$ for every non-negative integer $r$, then \[	au_k(n)\equiv0\pmod{(k-1)}. \] \end{proposition}  egin{proof} The pentagonal number theorem of Euler \cite{euler} allows us to write  egin{align} 
otag \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au_k(n)q^n&=q\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)^{k}\ &\label{tauk-rec}=\left(\sum_{r=1}^{\infty}	au_{k-1}(r)q^right)\left(\sum_{s=0}^{\infty}\omega(s)q^sight), \end{align} where $\omega(s)$ is as in (ef{PNT}). When equating the coefficients of $q^n$ at the extremes of the chain of equalities (ef{tauk-rec}), we obtain the following identity: \[ \label{identity1} \sum_{i=0}^{n-1}	au_{k-1}(n-i)\omega(i)=	au_{k}(n). \] If $	au_{k-1}(n-i)\equiv0\pmod{(k-1)}$ whenever $\omega(i)=\pm1$, then it follows that $	au_k(n)\equiv0\pmod{(k-1)}$. So a criterion for \[	au_{k-1}(n)\equiv0\pmod{(k-1)}\] is a requisite to proceed further. To that end, we define \[ T_{k-1}(q)=\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)^{k-1}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au_{k-1}(n)q^{n-1}. \] Now performing the operation $q rac{d}{dq}(\log{T_{k-1}(q)})$ and considering the Lambert's series expansion for the sum of positive divisors of $n$ (denoted $\sigma(n)$) we obtain  egin{equation}\label{recurrence} n	au_{k-1}(n+1)=-(k-1)\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}	au_{k-1}(i)\sigma(n+1-i)ight). \end{equation} Now we observe from the Identity (ef{recurrence}) that, if $\gcd(n,k-1)=1$, then $	au_{k-1}(n+1)\equiv 0\pmod{(k-1)}$. Since $k-1$ is a prime number, the condition $\gcd(n,k-1)=1$ is equivalent to the condition $n
ot\equiv 0\pmod{(k-1)}$. Thus, if $n
ot\equiv0\pmod{(k-1)}$ then $	au_{k-1}(n+1)\equiv0\pmod{(k-1)}$. This completes the proof. \end{proof}  egin{remark} Since the $	au$ function was introduced, an in-depth study over the value $	au(n)$ modulo ${23}$ is an important consideration. Mordell \cite{mordell-2} gave the following criterion for the divisibility of $	au(n)$ by 23: \[ 	au(23n+m)\equiv0\pmod{23} \] for $m\in\{5, 7, 10, 11, 14, 15, 17, 19, 20, 21, 22\}$. Here an application of Proposition ef{modulok-1} gives the following criterion: if $0\leq n-1- rac{3r^2\pm r}{2}
ot\equiv 0\pmod{23}$ for every non-negative integer $r$, then \[	au(n)\equiv0\pmod{23}. \] \end{remark} \subsection{ $	au_k(n)$ Modulo Divisors of $k$} Interestingly, by substituting any formal power series with integer coefficients, say $f(q)\in\mathbb{Z}[[q]]$, for $\prod\limits_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)$, one can further generalize Definition ef{main-definition}. Denote \[f(q)^{k}=a_0+a_1q+a_2q^2+\cdots. \] On differentiating with respect to $q$, we have \[k{f(q)}^{k-1}f'(q)=a_1+2a_2q+\cdots . \] This gives the relation \[na_{n}\equiv 0\pmod{|k|}. \] Now fixing $f(q)=\prod\limits_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)$ we have $a_n=	au_k(n+1)$. This observation yields the following result.  egin{proposition}\label{modulok} Let $n$ be a positive integer, and let $k$ be an integer with $\lvert kvert \geq 2$. Then we have \[ n	au_k(n+1)\equiv 0\pmod{|k|}. \] \end{proposition} The following result is a straightforward application of Proposition ef{modulok}.  egin{proposition}\label{modulo-divisorsofk} Let $m\geq 0$ and $k$ be integers such that $\lvert kvert\geq 2$. Then we have \[ 	au_k(|k|m+dr+1)\equiv0\left(	extrm{mod\ }{ rac{|k|}{d}}ight) \] for every $d\mid |k|$ such that $d<|k|$, and for every integer $r$ such that $\gcd(r, rac{|k|}{d})=1$. \end{proposition}  egin{proof} We have the congruence below based on Proposition ef{modulok}: \[n	au_k(n+1)\equiv0\pmod{|k|}. \] Given the aforementioned congruence and $\gcd(n,|k|)=d$, it can be deduced that \[ rac{n}{d}	au_k(n+1)\equiv0\left(	extrm{mod}{ rac{|k|}{d}}ight). \] Since $\gcd(n,|k|)=d$, for a positive integer $r$ satisfying $\gcd\left(r, rac{|k|}{d}ight)=1$, the integer $ rac{n}{d}$ must have the form $ rac{n}{d}= rac{|k|}{d}m+r$ for some integer $m\geq 0$. As a result, $n$ assumes the form $n=|k|m+dr$. \end{proof} The following list of congruences for $	au(n)$ modulo the divisors of 24 is obtained by substituting $24$ for $k$.  egin{proposition} For every integer $m\geq 0$, we have  egin{enumerate} \item $	au(24m+r+1)\equiv 0\pmod {24}$ for each $r\in\{1,5,7,11,13,17,19,23\}$; \item $	au(24m+r+1)\equiv 0\pmod{12}$ for each $r\in\{4,20\}$; \item $	au(24m+r+1)\equiv 0\pmod{8}$ for each $r\in\{3,9,6,15\}$; \item $	au(24m+r+1)\equiv 0\pmod{6}$ for each $r\in\{8,16\}$; \item $	au(24m+13)\equiv 0\pmod{4}$. \end{enumerate} \end{proposition} \section{ Representation of $	au_k(n)$ as a Partition Sum involving Binomial Coefficients} In this section, congruence properties of $	au_k(n)$ are derived using a partition sum representation (involving binomial coefficients) of $	au_k(n)$. Presenting the main results of this section requires the following definitions of partition theory.  egin{definition} 
ormalfont Let $n$ be a positive integer. By a {\it partition of $n$}, we mean a non-increasing sequence of positive integers whose sum equals $n$. Each element of the sequence is called a {\it part}. If each part, say $a_i$, appears $f_i$ times in a partition of $n$ then we denote that partition by $n=a_1^{f_1}\cdots a_r^{f_r}$. In this case $f_1, \cdots ,f_r$ are said to be the {\it frequencies} of the partition $a_1^{f_1}\cdots a_r^{f_r}$. \end{definition}  egin{definition} 
ormalfont Let $n$ and $t\geq 2$ be positive integers. If all of the parts of a partition of $n$ are not divisible by $t$, then the partition is called a {\it $t$-regular partition}. We denote the number of $t$-regular partitions of $n$ by $R_t(n)$. \end{definition} We note that the number of partitions of $n$ with parts from the set $\mathbb{N}\setminus t\mathbb{N}$ equals the number of $t$-regular partitions of $n$, from which the following equalities arise:  egin{align*} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}R_t(n)q^n&=\prod\limits_{r\in\mathbb{N}\setminus t\mathbb{N}} rac{1}{1-q^r}\ &=\prod_{s\in \mathbb{N}} rac{1-q^{ts}}{1-q^{ts}}\prod\limits_{r\in\mathbb{N}\setminus t\mathbb{N}} rac{1}{1-q^r}\ &=\prod_{m=1}^{\infty} rac{1-q^{tm}}{1-q^m}. \end{align*} This insight is one we utilize frequently in this section. We express $	au_k(n)$ as a binomial-coefficient-weighted partition sum in the following result.  egin{theorem}\label{binomial-representation} Let $k$ be a positive integer. We have  egin{description} \item{(a)}  egin{equation}\label{positive} 	au_k(n+1)=\sum_{\substack{n=a_1^{f_1}\cdots a_r^{f_r};\ f_i\leq k.}}(-1)^{f_1+\cdots f_r}{k\choose{f_1}}\cdots {k\choose{f_r}}, \end{equation} \item{(b)}  egin{equation}\label{negative} 	au_{-k}(n+1)=\sum_{\substack{n=a_1^{f_1}\cdots a_r^{f_r}}}{f_1+k-1\choose{k-1}}\cdots {f_r+k-1\choose{k-1}}. \end{equation} \end{description} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} We have  egin{align*} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au_k(n)q^n&=q\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)^k\ &=q\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left(1-{k\choose 1}q^{1\cdot m}+{k\choose 2}q^{2\cdot m}-\cdots +(-1)^{k}{k\choose k}q^{k\cdot m}ight). \end{align*} The above equality suggests that the value $(-1)^{f_1+f_2+\cdots +f_r}{k\choose {f_1}}{k\choose{f_2}}\cdots {k\choose{f_r}}$ contributes to the coefficient of $q^{n+1}$ for each partition of $n$ of the form $n=a_1^{f_1}\cdots a_r^{f_r}$ with the restriction $1\leq f_i\leq k$, and vice versa. Therefore, (a) is implied. We have  egin{align*} \sum_{n=1}^{\infty}	au_{-k}(n)q^n&=q\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)^{-k}\ &=q\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left({k-1\choose{k-1}}+{{(k-1)+1}\choose{k-1}}q^m+{(k-1)+2\choose{k-1}}q^{2m}+\cdotsight). \end{align*} The aforementioned equality suggests that the value ${{f_1+k-1}\choose{k-1}}\cdots {{f_r+k-1}\choose{k-1}}$ contributes to the coefficient of $q^{n+1}$ for each partition of $n$ of the type $n=a_1^{f_1}\cdots a_r^{f_r}$, and vice versa. Thus, (b) is implied. \end{proof} \subsection{ Parity Results connecting $	au_k(n)$ and $R_t(n)$ at Specific Instances of $k$ and $t$} We can get a parity result for $	au_{k}(n)$ (which involves a partition function) using the partition sum representation mentioned in Theorem ef{binomial-representation}.  egin{definition} Let $n$ be a positive integer and let $A$ be a set of positive integers. We define $F_A(n)$ to be the number of partitions of $n$ having each frequency from the set $A$. \end{definition}  egin{theorem}\label{parity-gen} Let $k$ be a positive integer. Let $A=\{a\in\mathbb N:a\leq k, {{k}\choose{a}}\equiv 1\pmod{2}\}$. We have  egin{equation} 	au_k(n+1)\equiv F_A(n)\pmod{2}. \end{equation} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} From the representation given in (ef{positive}) of Theorem ef{binomial-representation}, the proof follows immediately. \end{proof} Using Theorem ef{parity-gen}, we obtain a parity result for the $4$-regular partition function.  egin{theorem}\label{parityoftau} Let $n$ be a positive integer. We have  egin{equation} R_4(n)\equiv egin{cases}1\pmod{2}&{	ext { if }n= rac{m(m+1)}{2}};\ 0\pmod{2}&{	ext{ otherwise}}. \end{cases} \end{equation} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} We observe that ${24\choose k}\equiv 1\pmod 2$ if, and only if, $k\in\{8,16,24\}$. We may now write  egin{align*} 	au(n+1)&\equiv F_{\{8,16,24\}}(n)\pmod{2}, \end{align*} in accordance with Theorem ef{parity-gen}. As a result, $	au(n+1)\equiv 0\pmod{2}$ for each $n
ot\equiv 0\pmod{8}$. Therefore, the $n$ such that $n\equiv 0\pmod{8}$ is our primary concern. The partitions of $n$ that the function $F_{\{8,16,24\}}(n)$ counts when $n\equiv 0\pmod{8}$ can be expressed as follows: \[n=a_1^8a_2^{16}a_3^{24}.\] Alternatively expressed, \[ rac{n}{8}=a_1^1a_2^{2}a_3^{3}. \] Consequently, $F_{\{8,16,24\}}(8m)$ counts the number of partitions of $m$ whose frequencies do not exceed $3$. We denote the number of such partitions by $d_3(m)$. As can be seen,  egin{align} 
otag \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}d_3(n)q^n&=(1+q+q^2+q^3)(1+q^2+q^4+q^6)(1+q^3+q^6+q^9)\cdots \ &=\prod_{m=1}^{\infty} rac{1-q^{4m}}{1-q^m}\label{secondline}\ &
otag =\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1+q^m)(1+q^{2m}). \end{align} Considering that \[ \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}q(n)q^n=\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1+q^m) \] is the generating function for the number of partitions of $n$ with distinct parts (denoted $q(n)$), the equation  egin{equation}\label{d3} d_3(n)=\sum_{s=0}^{\lfloor rac{n}{2}floor}q(n-2s)q(s) \end{equation} is obtained from the above chain of equalities. We obtain \[q(s)\equiv \omega(s)\pmod 2,\] in light of Euler's Pentagonal Number theorem. Upon substituting this in Equation (ef{d3}), we obtain  egin{equation}\label{d3mod2} d_3(n)\equiv \sum_{s=0}^{\lfloor rac{n}{2}floor}q(n-2s)\omega(s)\pmod 2. \end{equation} In view of (i) of Theorem 3 in \cite{david}, we have  egin{equation}\label{d3final} \sum_{s=0}^{\lfloor rac{n}{2}floor}q(n-2s)\omega(s)= egin{cases} 1&	ext{ if $\delta_t(n)=1$};\ 0&	ext{ otherwise,} \end{cases} \end{equation} where \[\delta_t(n)= egin{cases} 1&	ext{ if $n= rac{m(m+1)}{2}$;}\ 0&	ext{ otherwise.} \end{cases} \] At this point, we can see from Equation (ef{secondline}) that $d_3(n)=R_4(n)$. Now the result follows from (ef{d3mod2}) and (ef{d3final}). \end{proof}  egin{remark} The congruence $d_3(n)\equiv 1\pmod 2$ is true only when $n= rac{m(m+1)}{2}$. This suggests that $	au(n+1)$ is odd only if $ rac{n}{8}= rac{m(m+1)}{2}$. Since $ rac{n}{8}= rac{m(m+1)}{2}$ simplifies to $n+1=(2m+1)^2$, it follows that $	au(n+1)$ is odd only if $n+1$ is an odd square. This is an established result. Ewell \cite{ewell-1} previously provided a proof. \end{remark}  egin{remark} The number of $4$-regular partitions of $n$ is equal to the number of partitions of $n$ with frequencies from the set $\{1,2,3\}$, as we have concluded in the previous theorem's proof. This equinumerous statement can be generalized in the way that follows: the number of $(t+1)$-regular partitions of $n$ is equal to the number of partitions of $n$ with frequencies from the set $\{1,2,\cdots, t\}$. This generalization may be validated by the su