e above chain of expressions, we will get the expected congruence. \end{proof} Utilizing the following Ramanujan's formula \cite[pp. 163-164]{hardy} for $	au(p^r)$: \[	au(p^r)= rac{p^{ rac{11}{2}r}}{\sin{\psi_p}}\sin{(r+1)\psi_p}, \] where $p$ is a prime number and $\cos{\psi_p}= rac{	au(p)}{2p^{ rac{11}{2}}}$, Lehmer \cite{Lehmer} gave an expression for $	au(n)\mod{23}$:  egin{equation}\label{lehmer} 	au(n)\equiv\sigma_{11}(n_1)2^t3^{ rac{-t}{2}}\prod\limits_{i=1}^{t}\sin{ rac{2\pi}{3}(1+\alpha_i)}\pmod{23}, \end{equation} where $n=n_1\prod\limits_{i=1}^{t}p_i^{\alpha_i}$, $p_i$s are the only prime factors of $n$ which are not of the form $u^2+23v^2$ but are quadratic residues of 23, and $\alpha_i$ is the exponent of the highest power of $p_i$ dividing $n$. We provide an expression for $	au(n)$ modulo $23$ in the following result, which is quite simple in comparison to (ef{lehmer}).  egin{theorem} Let $n$ be a positive integer. We have  egin{equation} 	au(n+1)\equiv\sum_{n= rac{3r^2\pm r}{2}+23	imes rac{3s^2\pm s}{2}}(-1)^{r+s}\pmod{23}. \end{equation} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Since \[{24\choose{k}}\equiv egin{cases} 1\pmod{23}&	ext{ if $k=0, 1, 23, 24$;}\ 0\pmod{23}&	ext{ otherwise,} \end{cases} \] we can write  egin{align*} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}	au(n+1)q^n &\equiv\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left(1-q^m-q^{23m}+q^{24m}ight)\pmod{23}\ &\equiv\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left[(1-q^m)(1-q^{23m})ight]\pmod{23}. \end{align*} Write \[\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left[(1-q^m)(1-q^{23m})ight]=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_nq^n. \] Now in accordance with Euler's pentagonal number theorem, we have \[a_n= egin{cases} (-1)^{r+s}&	ext{ if $n= rac{3r^2\pm r}{2}+23	imes rac{3s^2\pm s}{2}$;}\ 0&	ext{ otherwise.} \end{cases} \] While applying this observation in the tail end product of the above chain of expressions, we will get the intended congruence. \end{proof}  egin{theorem} Let $n$ be a positive integer. We have  egin{equation} 	au(n+1)\equiv \sum_{n=r+5 rac{s(s+1)}{2}+5 rac{3t^2\pm t}{2}}(-1)^{s+t}(2s+