this observation, we may write  egin{align*} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}	au_{p-1}(n+1)q^{n}&\equiv\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left(1+q^{m}+\cdots +q^{(p-1)m}ight)\pmod{p}\ &\equiv\prod_{m=1}^{\infty} rac{1-q^{pm}}{1-q^m}\pmod{p}\ &\equiv\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}R_p(n)q^n\pmod{p}. \end{align*} Now the result follows. \end{proof} \section{ Divisibility of Partition Function Weighted Composition Sums } The Ramanujan's congruences for the partition function are as follows:  egin{description} \item{(a)} $p(5n+4)\equiv 0\pmod{5}$, \item{(b)} $p(7n+5)\equiv 0\pmod{7}$, \item{(c)} $p(11n+6)\equiv 0\pmod{11}$. \end{description} It is rare to find such a simple congruence for other larger primes. The following congruence (modulo $l$, an odd prime), involving partition function values, is found in this section:  egin{equation*} \sum_{\substack{{n=a_1+a_2+\cdots a_k}\{a_{i}\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}}}}p(a_{1})p(a_{2})\cdots p(a_{k})\equiv \sum_{n=t+ls}	au_{l-k}(t)p(s)\pmod{l}. \end{equation*} The following lemma is crucial in obtaining the above congruence.  egin{lemma}\label{binomialmodulooddprime} Let $l$ be an odd prime number. Let $k$ be an integer such that $1\leq k<l$. Let $n\geq 0$ be an integer. Let $r$ be the remainder obtained by division of $n$ into $l$. We have  egin{equation} {{n+k}\choose{k}}\equiv  egin{cases}(-1)^{r}{{l-k-1}\choose{r}}\pmod{l}&	ext{ when $r\in\{0,1,\cdots ,l-k-1\}$;}\ 0\pmod{l}&	ext{when $r\in\{l-k,\cdots ,l-1\}$.} \end{cases} \end{equation} \end{lemma}  egin{proof} Consider the following expression: \[{{n+k}\choose{k}}= rac{(n+k)(n+k-1)\cdots (n+1)}{k!}. \] Using this representation, we find an expression for ${n+k}\choose{k}$ modulo $l$. Assume that $n=sl+r$ for some $r\in\{l-1,l-2,\cdots ,l-k\}$. Then $(n+k)(n+k-1)\cdots (n+1)\equiv 0\pmod{l}$. Since $l$ is a prime number and $k<l$, we obtain $ rac{(n+k)(n+k-1)\cdots (n+1)}{k!}\equiv0\pmod{l}$. That is, ${{n+k}\choose{k}}\equiv 0\pmod{l}$ when $r\in\{l-k,\cdots ,l-1\}$. The second case follows. Assume that $n=sl+r$ for some $r\in\{0,1,\cdots ,l-k-1\}$. Since $l$ is a prime number and $k<l$, we obtain  egin{align*} {{n+k}\choose{k}}&= rac{(sl+r+k)(sl+r+k-1)\cdots (sl+r+1)}{k!}\ &= rac{s^{*}l}{k!}+ rac{(r+k)(r+k-1)\cdots (r+1)}{k!}\ &\equiv {{r+k}\choose {k}}\pmod{l}\ &\equiv{{r+k}\choose{r}}\pmod{l}. \end{align*} On the other hand, we have  egin{align*} (-1)^r{{l-k-1}\choose{r}}&=(-1)^r rac{(l-k-1)(l-k-2)\cdots (l-k-1-(r-1))}{r!}\ &=(-1)^r rac{(l-(k+1))(l-(k+2))\cdots (l-(k+r))}{r!}\ &=(-1)^r\left( rac{s^{'}l}{k!}+(-1)^r rac{(k+1)(k+2)\cdots (k+r)}{r!}ight)\ &\equiv (-1)^r(-1)^r{{r+k}\choose{r}}\pmod{l}. \end{align*} From the above two congruences, we have the relation \[{{n+k}\choose{k}}\equiv(-1)^r{{l-k-1}\choose{r}}\pmod{l} \] when $k<l$. The proof is now completed. \end{proof} Now we are equipped to prove the following main result of this section.  egin{theorem}\label{compositionsum} Let $k\geq 2$ be a positive integer. Let $l> k$ be an odd prime number. Let $p(n)$ be the number of partitions of $n$. We have  egin{equation} 	au_{-k}(n+1)\equiv\sum_{n=t+ls}	au_{l-k}(t)p(s)\pmod{l}. \end{equation} In another notation,  egin{equation} \sum_{\substack{{n=a_1+a_2+\cdots a_k}\{a_{i}\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}}}}p(a_{1})p(a_{2})\cdots p(a_{k})\equiv \sum_{n=t+ls}	au_{l-k}(t)p(s)\pmod{l}. \end{equation} \end{theorem}  egin{proof} We have  egin{align*} \prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)^{-k}&=\sum_{n=0}^\infty	au_{-k}(n+1)q^n\ &=1+\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left(\sum_{\substack{{n=a_1+a_2+\cdots a_k}\{a_{i}\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}}}}p(a_{1})p(a_{2})\cdots p(a_{k})ight)q^n. \end{align*} This equality permits us to present the congruence of this result in two different forms. Now in accordance with Lemma ef{binomialmodulooddprime}, we may write  egin{align*} \prod_{m=1}^{\infty}(1-q^m)^{-k}&=\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left(\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}{{n+k-1}\choose{k-1}}q^{mn}ight)\ &\equiv\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left[\left(\sum_{r=0}^{l-k}(-1)^r{{l-k}\choose{r}}q^{rm}ight)\left(1-q^{lm}ight)^{-1}ight]\pmod{l}\ &\equiv\prod_{m=1}^{\infty}\left[(1-q^m)^{l-k}\left(1-q^{lm}ight)^{-1}ight]\pmod{l}. \end{align*} Now the result follows. \end{proof}  egin{corollary} Let $p(n)$ be the number of partitions of $n$. We have  egin{equation} \sum_{\substack{{a+b=n}\a,b\in\mathbb N\cup\{0\}}}p(a)p(b)\equiv \sum_{n=t+3s}\omega(t)p(s)\pmod{3}, \end{equation} where $\omega(t)$ is given in (ef{PNT}). \end{corollary}  egin{proof} Fix $l=3$ and $k=2$ in Theorem ef{compositionsum}. Now the result follows as a consequence of the observation $	au_1(n)=\omega(n)$. \end{proof} Let $l\geq 5$ be a prime number. In view of Identity (ef{JTPI}), we find a sufficient condition for the following congruence: \[\sum_{\substack{{n=a_1+a_2+\cdots +a_{l-3}}\{a_{i}\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}}}}p(a_{1})p(a_{2})\cdots p(a_{l-3})\equiv 0\pmod{l}. \]  egin{corollary} Let $l\geq 5$ be a prime number. For non-zero integer $n$, let $R(n, l)$ denote the remainder obtained by division of $n$ into $l$. If $m$ is a non-negative integer such that $m
ot\equiv s\pmod{l}$ for every $$s\in ig\{0 ig\}\cup igg\{R\left((-1)^r{{l-3}\choose{r}}, light):0\leq r\leq rac{l-3}{2} igg\},$$ then for $n\equiv m\pmod{l}$ we have  egin{equation} \sum_{\substack{{n=a_1+a_2+\cdots a_{l-3}}\{a_{i}\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{0\}}}}p(a_{1})p(a_{2})\cdots p(a_{l-3})\equiv 0\pmod{l}. \end{equation} \end{corollary}  egin{proof} Assume the following:  egin{enumerate} \item $m
